{
  "text": "Several genome-wide association studies have demonstrated that host SNPs near the IL28B gene are associated with SVR to the treatment with peginterferon alfa and ribavirin in chronic hepatitis C patients [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . These SNPs are also associated with spontaneous clearance of HCV in acute HCV infection. The various distributions of IL28B polymorphisms among different populations worldwide may, at least partly, explain the heterogeneity in the responses to interferon-based treatments among different ethnic groups. The IL28B SNPs are strongly associated with SVR rates in patients who are infected with HCV GT-1 or GT-4 and receive combination treatment with peginterferon alfa and ribavirin [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] . However, the association between IL28B variations and treatment response in patients infected with HCV GT-2 or GT-3 is still controversial [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] .",
